Giussani acutely points out that most of the following examples seem not to agree with the rule given. A spider’s weh, for instance, must, owing to its length, touch many atoms of soul: it is much larger than the point of a needle, to which atoms of the soul respond readilyenough. In this case the important clement is lightness (cf. l. 387), not smaliness. It seems likely that, according to Epicurus, there are no atoms of soul on the absolute surface of the body, so that a very light object, even if of some length, touches atoms ol the body only, whereas a beavier object, by carrying its impression deeper, does reach atoms of the soul. And 1 think Lucr. may have intended to express this here: in fact, the intervalla are not of superficies, but of profundity.
